{
  "doc_id": "49013",
  "text": "The annual kidney function decline of -1.3 ml/min/ 1.73 m 2 observed in our study is lower than the À2.2 ml/min/1.73 m 2 for post-MI patients found in the Prevention of Renal and Vascular End-stage Disease study, possibly because the patients in our cohort received more optimal cardiovascular drug treatment. [CITATION_1] Other researchers have reported a mean annual eGFR decline of À1.0 ml/min/1.73 m 2 in a community-based cohort (mean age 55 years) and À1.8 ml/min/1.73 m 2 in healthy individuals (mean age 72 years). [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] The size of the association between high BMI and WC on kidney function decline that we found was small. However, a persistently slower kidney function decline may postpone or prevent chronic kidney disease (CKD) in patients at high risk, which is clinically relevant. In addition, we recently showed in the Alpha Omega Cohort Study a linear increase in mortality risk (cardiovascular and non-cardiovascular) for patients with an eGFR below 80 ml/min/1.73 m 2 . [CITATION_4] Preservation of kidney function is therefore important, especially in these high-risk patients.",
